This paper is primarily focused on the loss surface of deep neural networks, which is a key topic in the field of machine learning. The paper provides theoretical results that apply to a wide range of activation functions and loss functions, which suggests that it is likely to be relevant to several sub-categories of computer science. Specifically, the paper's focus on deep learning and optimization makes it likely to be relevant to the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper's focus on fully connected networks and its potential applications to image and signal processing suggest that it may also be relevant to the sub-categories of cs.CV (Computer Vision) and cs.SI (Signal and Image Processing).
